# direnv — Admiral Bash's Island Adventure  (TEMPLATE)
# ============================================================================
# Copy this to `.envrc`, then run `direnv allow` once in this directory:
#     cp .envrc.example .envrc && direnv allow
#
# `.envrc` is gitignored (machine-local); this `.example` is the version that
# travels with the repo so a co-instructor cloning it knows the pattern.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Points KUBECONFIG at a project-local kubeconfig so kubectl / just / helm /
# k9s always target the lab's k3d cluster while you work in this repo.
#
# Why this exists:
#   If k3s is also installed on this machine, its `kubectl` binary defaults to
#   the root-only /etc/rancher/k3s/k3s.yaml. Lab commands then hit the wrong
#   cluster — or fail with a permission error. An explicit KUBECONFIG overrides
#   every such default.
#
# `just bootstrap-k3d` writes the k3d cluster's credentials to .kube/config
# (gitignored). The justfile sets this same path for `just` recipes, so `just`
# works with or without direnv — this file extends it to your interactive
# shell (hand-typed kubectl, k9s, helm).
#
# Requires direnv (https://direnv.net):
#   brew install direnv          # macOS
#   sudo apt install direnv      # Debian / Ubuntu
# Add the direnv hook to your shell, then run once in this directory:
#   direnv allow
# ============================================================================
export KUBECONFIG="$PWD/.kube/config"
